posts.name: gabby
posts.cooked:
We don’t have a drivetrain yet and the internet is not helping. We don’t have any mentors to help us. We are literally on our own. We just want our robot to drive in 3 days or else our advisor won’t let us go to competition.

We are using cim motors, differential drive, and coding in java.

//github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/tree/main/wpilibjExamples/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/examples/differentialdrivebot

This is what you’re looking for. If you have other code then you can copy these files to it otherwise you can create this directly as an example in WPILib project creator.
Reach out to 3-5 of the FRC teams nearest you.  I’m sure one of them will be willing to spend an evening to help you.

posts.name: alst
posts.cooked:
Hollisms:

I’m sure one of them will be willing to spend an evening to help you.

Also, worst case: there are 37 other teams at your competition next week, and at least some of them will have people to spare that can help you. On top of that, there are volunteers (CSAs, etc.) that can help with code. Many inspectors also have experience with building robots and can help as needed. If your only issue right now is that your robot doesn’t have code to drive, you should absolutely still go to your event.

At my event last week, we had about 4 robots with no code whatsoever Thursday night, and 2 with no bumpers either. All of them passed inspection and were driving on the field during their first match on Friday. You aren’t the only ones in need of help.

(“you” referring to the original post)

posts.name: Max Morehead
posts.cooked:
You should tell your advisor that you should go to the event anyways even if the robot can’t drive. Teams have had successful events after not having a working robot at the beginning of the regional in the past. I will be at the central valley regional, and based on how my team is currently doing I will be able to devote a good amount of time to helping you. There will be other teams there with more capacity to help.

How much of your drivetrain have you finished? Have you finished wiring the robot? What type of motor controllers are you using and how are they connected to the Roborio? Can you take a picture of the robot, in particular including all the wiring? How much of the robot have you built? Just a drivetrain or something more? We have a mostly constructed kitbot shooter that I will probably be able to bring to the regional.

If you download the code at the link @crueter posted and make sure the motor controllers are plugged into the correct PWM ports, you should be able to run the code without changes. Have you made any progress on the code? If so upload your full code to github and share it here.

What day are you coming to the regional, Thursday night or Friday morning? Would a video call with someone during your build time help?

Going to echo what others have said. Go to your event. At our event in week 1 our students helped 4 teams with software and electrical work to get their tank or swerve drives moving.

People are there to help each other out, do your best and ask for help for the rest.

You’re attending one event - meaning not going to that event means your advisor is losing out on a $6000 learning opportunity.
Go to your event. Find help. Our team helped another fix an extremely serious software problem, and we also received help when we lost our internet cables. People will help you out.

Yes, absolutely go to your event, no matter what state your robot is in.

Not going would waste your team’s registration fees for the event, but would also deprive your team of the opportunity to work with other teams in your area to get your robot on the field. You would also be depriving other teams of the opportunity to have their students help you. These “coopetition” moments are actually some of the best learning experiences you can get out of FRC .

I have heard stories of teams arriving at competitions with the AM14U kitbot chassis in its unopened box on a Friday, and they were still playing by Saturday. Nobody wants to see your team unable to play.

Stay positive and stay focused. It may feel overwhelming, but you are very close to having a working robot. Follow the code examples linked above, and keep asking questions here. You’ll get it.

posts.name: Mr. Siefen | 453
posts.cooked:
veg:

I have heard stories of teams arriving at competitions with the AM14U kitbot chassis in its unopened box on a Friday, and they were still playing by Saturday. Nobody wants to see your team unable to play.

Have seen this too many times at FIM events in the past. Usually it’s a team with 1 teacher who was given it by admin and told it’s a competition, you go there, build a robot and that’s it. They never know that you’re supposed to do it ahead of time.

At least OPs team has something together.

Point still stands everyone else around instantly jumped in to get something together and teams kept checking in throughout the event trying to help them add scoring abilities.

This year with KitBot we have spare parts and the manuals for the base, upper half and enhancements that FIRST provided in a binder in case someone needs it.
